ectors; industrial process control of fuel cells and lung function diagnostics. This includes collaboration with industrial partners at Rolls-Royce and new academic and clinical partners at the University of Oxford.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>0C3A393A-A381-40EC-A25A-E3523F775F76</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>56dea4b41b8106.83746100</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Aerospace, Defence and Marine,Agriculture, Food and Drink,Chemicals,Environment,Healthcare,Pharmaceuticals and Medical Biotechnology</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutput><gtr:description>The dataset comprises of measurements and simulations obtained with a prototype miniaturised photoacoustic trace gas sensor in combination with a prototype Raman Fibre Amplifier system for operation at 1651nm. Both systems were tested individually and their combined application for trace gas sensing of Methane (CH4) was investigated.
